  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Common questions about credit card eligibility and approval</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What is the minimum CIBIL score required for a credit card?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Most banks require a minimum CIBIL score of 700 for standard credit card approval. A score of 750 or above significantly improves your chances and qualifies you for premium cards with better rewards and higher limits. If your score is between 600-700, you can still apply for entry-level cards or co-branded cards from select banks. For scores below 600, secured credit cards backed by a fixed deposit are the best option to build your credit history while enjoying card benefits.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Can I get a credit card without income proof?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Yes, in certain cases. If you have a fixed deposit with a bank, you can apply for a secured credit card without traditional income proof — the FD serves as your collateral and determines your credit limit (typically 80-90% of FD value). Students with a parent as guarantor can also get student credit cards without personal income proof. Additionally, if you hold a savings account with high average balance, some banks offer pre-approved credit cards based on your banking relationship rather than income documents.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Does checking eligibility affect my CIBIL score?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              No, TrueCred's eligibility checker uses a soft credit inquiry that does not impact your CIBIL score. Soft inquiries are informational checks that don't get recorded as credit applications. Only when you formally submit a credit card application does the bank perform a hard inquiry, which may temporarily reduce your score by 5-10 points. This is why we recommend checking eligibility first through our platform to identify cards you're likely to be approved for before applying.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            Why was my credit card application rejected?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              Common reasons for credit card rejection include: (1) Low CIBIL score (below 700), (2) Insufficient or unstable income, (3) High existing debt-to-income ratio (EMIs exceeding 50% of income), (4) Recent loan defaults, settlements, or write-offs, (5) Too many credit card applications in a short period, (6) Incomplete or incorrect documentation. If rejected, wait at least 3-6 months before reapplying, and use the waiting period to improve your score by paying existing dues on time and reducing outstanding balances.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            How can I improve my credit card eligibility?
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              You can improve your credit card eligibility by: (1) Maintaining a CIBIL score above 750 through timely payments, (2) Keeping credit utilisation below 30% on existing cards, (3) Avoiding multiple credit applications in a short span, (4) Building a relationship with your bank through a savings account or FD, (5) Ensuring stable employment with at least 1 year of work experience, (6) Paying off existing high-interest debt to lower your debt-to-income ratio. If you have no credit history, start with a secured credit card to build a track record.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

